America, Two Types of Citizens
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting ballots for the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the results are finally determined, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is expected in this fiercely contested, record-breaking voter turnout election.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the presidential election, but this choice affects people everywhere.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
On the positive side, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter participation has remained high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
The courts are investigating a decision by the U.S. Postal Service that appears to be politically motivated, which hindered the delivery of ballots from regions where votes are expected to mainly come from the Democratic Party.
The current U.S. president, Trump, made an unsubstantiated claim of victory late Tuesday evening, which received almost no response, and his demand to stop the vote counting (at least in the states where he is leading) seems to have been ignored.
However, it is concerning that the division among U.S. voters remains significant.
The votes for the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The seats for governors and state legislatures are almost evenly divided between the two parties (with Republicans having a slight advantage).
The expected "blue wave" for the Democratic Party did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, probably securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democratic Party actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not come from strong authorization, nor does it stem from political adjustments.
Trump's polling situation is very good, having received 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter among all U.S. presidential candidates in history, surpassing any previous winner.
Especially notable is that this occurred against the backdrop of daily new coronavirus cases reaching record highs, with over 100,000 new cases and over 1,000 deaths per day.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic were becoming the most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he himself does not run, in the next presidential election in 2024, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of President Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will still be a powerful force.
It is no surprise that, despite having no evidence, Trump has done everything to appear virtuous and upright, and has attempted to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accused of fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden as president.
Trump is very likely to never concede, and even less likely to attend the swearing-in ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never encountered a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They classify themselves into different communities and regions based on shared viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national citizen curriculum provides convenience for the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that the division of the nation in most cases is not along economic lines.
Voters from all social strata cast their votes for the two candidates, and the voting patterns of population, gender, and race are not as one-sided as many people predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Education level is obviously an indicator of political orientation, and geographical location is also the case. Republican voters tend to reside in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to reside in metropolitan areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against this background, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms in the way the presidential election or the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who will suffer losses from change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This will largely depend on the judgment of Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell, as well as his ability and willingness to cooperate with the incoming Biden president.
Cooperation will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly be resisted by the more ideologically rigid members of his party.
Democrats have tried to sharply reject everything that Trump represents.
But they did not succeed.
And the Republicans sought an election that would legitimize Trump.
But this also did not go as they wished.
On the contrary, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
